 claimant right on debt and disposed investment of Theparak Transformers Co.,Ltd. In 
this regard, the Company w
ill have no longer business transaction with Theparak Transformers Co.,Ltd. again.
 This is complying with the connected transaction policy of AKR which were approved
 by the Board of director on February 23, 2006.  
  
4. Related Person : Nepal Ekarat Engineering Co.,Pvt.Ltd.
Types of Relationship:              In 2005, no relations (2004 joint-venture) 
         Before December 30, 2004, the company holds 47.50 per cent of total shares
 at Nepal Ekarat Engineering Co.,Pvt.Ltd. Therefore, Nepal Ekarat Engineering Co.,
Pvt.Ltd. was a associated company of AKR. Having Mr. Kietphong Noichaiboon 
(Chief Executive Officer) have direct shares of 4,027,280 shares or 0.66 per cent 
who has authority over Ekarat Holdings Co.,Ltd. with 34,347,750 shares or 5.65 
per cent and Mr. Wiwat Sangtian being the Managing Director holding 136,640 
shares or 0.02 per cent. 
         After December 30, 2004, all shares of Nepal Ekarat Engineering Co.,Pvt.Ltd
were sold to E.K.R. Holdings Co.,Ltd. to cause Nepal Ekarat Engineering Co.,
Pvt.Ltd. is no longer a joint-venture but has authority over the management of Nepal 
Ekarat Engineering Co.,Pvt.Ltd. since Mr. Danucha Noichaiboon, Mr. Surasak
 Noichaiboon, Mr. Wisut Topongkasem and Mrs. Daranee Kantamara still hold
 828,610 share or 0.16 per cent of the authorized share capital issued and paid up 
shares capital at E.K.R. Holdings amount of 75,000 shares or 75 per cent of the 
authorized share capital. Nepal Ekarat Engineering Co.,Pvt.Ltd. still has a joint 
director and management - Mr. Kiettiphong Noichaiboon and Mr. Wiwat Sangtian 
After June 29, 2005, AKR is not related to the management and the shareholders
 of Nepal Ekarat Engineering Co.,Pvt.Ltd. and E.K.R. Holdings Co.,Ltd. since
 the management and the shareholders of AKR who holding E.K.R. Holding Co.,Ltd.
 sold off the shares of E.K.R. Holdings Co.,Ltd to the non-related persons: Mr.Pirom
 Chanpittayakit, Mr.Chalermphol Chaiyu and Mr.Saengchai Ekpattanapanich and
 AKR's management already resigned from Nepal Ekarat Engineering Co.,Pvt.Ltd.
4.1 Types and Value of transactions:    
          On December 30, 2004 Nepal Ekarat Engineering Co.,Pvt.Ltd. have trade
 accounts receivable and advance unpaid payment of Baht 5,558,236.43 and Baht 
989,461.78 respectively. The company gained profit from foreign exchange during
 January-June 2005 in the amount of Baht 5,769.18 so Nepal Ekarat Engineering
 Co.,Pvt.Ltd. have unpaid in the amount of Baht 6,553,467.39. On March 24, 2005, 
AKR transferred the claimant right on debt to E.K.R. Holdings Co.,Ltd. with the 
compensation of Baht 10,000 with a condition of 70 per cent of the amount of
 exceeding the purchased debt price of each company after deduction of related 
expenses within 3 years commencing from the day of transferred

.Necessity and Reasonableness 
        The Audit Committee opined that the accounts receivables occurred from product 
sales at market price and advance must be paid up from administrative expenses when
 Nepal Ekarat Engineering Co.,Pvt.Ltd. was still a associated company until AKR sold 
off shareholders' equity with transfer claimant right on debt. Nepal Ekarat Engineering
 Co.,Pvt.Ltd. The liabilities will paid up September 2005 with no business operation
 with Nepal Ekarat Engineering Co.,Pvt.Ltd. decided by Board of Directors.
4.2 Types & value of transaction:       
         The company is committed with 2 banks to issue a letter of credit for a credit o
f US$ 400,000 or Baht 16 million (exchange rate: 40 baht = US$1) to Nepal Ekarat
 Engineering Co.,Pvt.Ltd. The company had release the guarantee of US$ 200,000 on
 January 11, 2006 and US$ 200,000 on February 2, 2006 respectively. From February
 2, 2006 onwards the company has no commitment with the letter of credit with Nepal
 Ekarat Engineering Co.,Pvt.Ltd.
Necessity and Reasonableness
        The Audit Committee opined that connected transaction that credits guarantee
 with the bank in order to deal business with Nepal Ekarat Engineering Co.Pvt.Ltd.
 since Nepal Ekarat Engineering Co.,Pvt.Ltd. was still a business partner but AKR
 had sold off shareholders's equity and transferred claimant right on debt on December 
30, 2004 and March 24, 2005 respectively. The Audit Committee already followed
 up management to released all the guarantee with no business operations with Nepal 
Ekarat Engineering Co.,Pvt.Ltd.

5. Related person : Ekarat Land and Development Co.,Ltd. 
Relationship:
         Mr. Kietphong Noichaiboon is the only authorized Managing Director holding 40
 per cent of shares at Ekarat Land & Development Co.,Ltd. and has 6.31 per cent
 authority to control Ekarat Holdings Co.,Ltd. with Mr. Darunwat Noichaiboon, Mrs. 
Daranee Kantamara, Mr. Surasak Noichaiboon and Mr. Dhanucha Noichaiboon holding
 10 per cent and 0.12 per cent shares of Ekarat Land & Development Co.,LtdTypes and 
Value of transactions:In 1998, Ekarat Land & Development Co.,Ltd. purchased land at 
Baht 17,000,000 (136 rai 1 ngan 67 square Wahs located at Amphur Khok Samrong,
 Lopburi province). The company paid for tax and expenses of Baht 923,336 and land 
value tax of Baht 17,923,336. The amount of Baht 5,500,000 land had been paid in 1998.
 On December 31, 2005, total amount of Baht 11,500,000 had been paid. On October
 2005, Ekarat Land & Development Co.,Ltd.  reduced the liabilities of land to Baht 
6,000,000. The company is committed to pay the remaining of Baht 5,500,000 by
 transferring the land rights from Ekarat Land and Development Co.,Ltd. to Ekarat 
Chemical Co.,Ltd. to pay off the liabilities (liabilities between Ekarat Land and Development
 Co.,Ltd. and Ekarat Chemical Co.,Ltd) having Ekarat Chemical Co.,Ltd. holding 
12.42 per cent land rights (94 rai 2 ngans 19 square wahs)  from the 17.92 portion. Ekarat
 Chemicals also hold 5.50 portions (41 rai 3 ngans 48 square wahs) from the 17.92 
portion, making a profit of Baht 11,162,388 (using the prices appraised by independent 
appraisers - The Valuation & Consultants Co.,Ltd. on December 9, 2004 with appraisal
 at Baht 1.1 million) Ekarat Chemical Co.,Ltd. did not separate the land deed between 
Ekarat Land and Development Co.,Ltd. for the unpaid liabilities for future sales so no
payment is made for separating the land deed. 

Necessity and Reasonableness:
The connected transactions which AKR used the land as guarantee with the financial institute. 
At the present the land is financially free and the Audit Committee agreed that the land 
can be divided for the company's benefits. 

6. Related Person: V&A Holdings Co.,Ltd.
Relationship:
         V&A Holdings Co.,Ltd. holds 21,959,190 shares or 3.61 per cent and Sold off 
99,993 shares at Ekarat Solar Co.,Ltd. to AKR.  6.1 Types and Value of Transaction:
Loans are made from V&A Holdings Co.,Ltd. at Baht 330.00 million to follow 
rehabilitation plan. The company had issued a promissory note MLR-4% interest
 rate with remaining liabilities of Baht 30.00 million and interest rate of 1.75 per cent 
collectible at the end of 2005. Necessity and Reasonableness:The connected transaction 
is reasonable, owing to the Conditions proceeded to the rehabilitation plan with lower
 market interest rate at MLR-4%. AKR will repayment the residual load after listed in SET.
6.2 Types and value of transactions:
On September 27, 2004, AKR invested in Ekarat Solar Co.,Ltd by purchased 99,993
 shares from V&A Holdings at Baht 10 per share totaling to Baht 999,930 or 99 per
cent of share capital and in that day AKR Increased registered share capital in Ekarat Solar
 Co.,Ltd. amount to 2,900,000 shares at Baht 10 per share (ordinary share at par value 
of Baht 10 each) so AKR invested in Ekarat Solar Co.,Ltd. in total amount of Baht 29,999
,930 or 99.99 per cent. Since Ekarat Solar Co., Ltd. was established on April 9, 2004
no business operated.
Necessity and Reasonableness:
         'The connectd transaction is reasonable since Ekarat Solar Co.,Ltd. was established
since April 9, 2004 until in the occurring transaction day Ekarat Solar Co.,Ltd no business
being operated.
         The Audit Committee had considering the connected transactions and agreed
 that the transactions are normal with norelated persons or conflict of interest to
 the company  Future Policy of Transactions 
         AKR's Board of Directors Approval at Board of Directors Meeting No. 
3/2549 dated February 23, 2006 on the connected transactions have been made
 as follow:1. AKR have a policy not to handle any connected transactions with
 any subsidiary or relatedcompanies which sold off as follows:   
(1) E.K.R. Holding Co., Ltd.
(2) Ekarat Marketing Co., Ltd.
(3) Ekarat International Co., Ltd.
(4) E.R. Metal Work Co., Ltd.
(5) Ekarat Generator Co., Ltd.
(6) Teeparak Transformer Co., Ltd.
(7) Myanmar Ekarat Transformer Co.,Ltd
(8) Nepal Ekarat Engineering Co.Pvt.Ltd. 
(9) Ekarat Transformer(M) Sdn.Bhd.
2. Connected transactions between AKR and its subsidiary company, Ekarat Solar
 Co.,Ltd.,  has a policy to handle connected transactions as follow
(1) Normal commercial transactions and under general commercial conditions  
         The management is to report the transactions under normal commercial terms 
transactionsto the AKR's Board of Directors every month via the Audit Committee.  
(2) Transactions related to property and other services  
         AKR's management should request AKR's Board of Directors and/or cases by
 case of the shareholders' meeting approve for transaction related to property and 
other services worth Baht 500,000 per transaction such as acquisition and disposition
 of assets, offer assets, permission to use assets, offer or receipt of assets servicing,
 sale and purchase of securities and new securities to be issued In the regard.
 The Audit Committee must provide its opinion before approval
         Any transactions related to assets or other services worth less than Baht 
500,000 per transaction must be reported to the Audit Committee and AKR's Board 
of Directors at the next AKR's Board of Directors meeting. 
(3) Financial assistance transaction 
         Financial assistance means financial assistance for loans using assets and
 property as collateral or any transactions similar to. The management should
 approve the transaction at AKR's Board of Directors  and/or cases by case 
of the shareholders' meeting with an approval from the Audit Committee first. 
3. The Connected transactions between AKR and other related companies or 
related persons
          The company managements have to approve at AKR's Board of Directors 
and/or cases by case of the shareholders' meeting with an approval from the
 Audit Committee first.
           The management and Board of Directors must perform accordingly to the
 legal aspects and notification of the SET as well as the disclosure of information 
that are concerning connected transaction and the acquisition and disposition 
of assets of AKR or subsidiary companies as specified by Federation of 
Accounting Professions (FAP).
Contingencies and Commitments                             -None-
Risk Factors
Risk in depending on selling transformers to specific customers
         Most of the company's revenues come from selling distribution transformers.
 The highest orders from its customers were PEA and EGAT, approximately 
26.70 per cent of total sales and services revenues. If the company was to lose
 these 2 giant customers, the company's revenue will be affected.  However, the
 chance is minimal since the company is improving the quality of the distribution
 transformer to be accepted nationwide. Since 1986, the company provided the
 best service since to be generally accepted by the public and private sectors
 so the company was very competitive. At the same time, the company has
 a policy to distribute its products and services to its target customers.  

Risk of the fluctuation in cost of raw materials of distribution transformers
         The main sales revenue of transformers come from using local and 
imported raw materials such as silicon steel, bronze sheet and bronze steel, 
etc. The cost of raw materials is 80 per cent of the cost to produce all the 
distribution transformers; therefore, the company may be affected by the
 fluctuation cost of raw material in the world. However, for the past 20 years
 Since the evolution of transformers,the company plans to manage the raw
 materials and reserve the raw materials to use for its production for 3 months
. The company also adjusts the average price of the distribution transformer
 to be in accordance to the rising price of raw materials to maintain its gross
 profit, margin in 2003, 2004, and 2005 at a satisfaction level of 28.15, 28.91
 and 27.19 per cent respectively.   

Risk from shortage of solar cell
         The Solar Module that Ekarat Solar Co., Ltd produces is made from
 solar cell as mainly raw material that comes from pure silicon. The Solar
 Cell Manufacturer may not have sufficient solar cells and may have difficulty
 getting solar cell to produce solar module for the customers' demands.
 Nevertheless, Ekarat Solar Co.,Ltd. had prevented the problem by contacting 
Bp Solar(Australia) Co., Ltd. , from Australia, Q-Cells AG, Germany, etc. so
 that Ekarat Solar Co.,Ltd. can plan an advance order of the raw materials to
 produce sufficient solar module. In addition, Ekarat Solar Co.,Ltd. plans to
 produce and order solar cell advance for 2 months.  

Risk from fluctuation in cost of solar cell 
        For the past 20 years, the price of Solar Cell is lowered. From 1997
 onwards, the world demand rate for solar cell has increase to an average of 
38.38 per cent per year. Since 2004, the solar cell manufacturer faced problems
 of insufficient solar-grade silicon used to manufacture solar module, as a result
 affecting the increasing price of solar cell since 2004 until now. The high price
 of solar cell will affect the cost of solar module to rise and in turn affect the
 profit of the company. Ekarat SolarCo.,Ltd. protects the risk by investigating
 the price of the solar cell and reserve the raw materials in advance to control
 the cost of capital investment by setting the price in accordance to the 
increasing price of  raw materials.

 Risk of Guarantee of Subsidiary
         CompanyEkarat Solar Co.,Ltd. is under the process of establishing a 
solar cell factory worth Baht 1,400 million by proposing to increase its shares
 capital Baht 470 million and loans from banks of Baht 900 million to purchase
 machines and Baht 450 million for working capital. Ekarat Solar Co.,Ltd. had 
signed a contract with guaranteed the loansof Baht 1,350 million another 
condition involved AKR is the pledging of the Ekarat Solar Co.,Ltd. ordinary
 share, held by AKR, at 99.99 percent or not less than 51 percent if the have
 been sold off to other joint investors. Therefore, AKR is at risk and there 
are conditions to the loans for the unexpected production result. However
, the company and its subsidiary company have a contingency plan to operate
 the solar cell factory as the company has already placed order of machines
 from the leading companies such as M+W Zander(Thai) LTD and Centrotherm
Photovoltaics GmbH + Co.KG and hiring S.D.C. Co.,Ltd and Dr. Sorawit 
Saikasem as consultant until the project is complete. Ekarat Solar Co.,Ltd.
 received good cooperation from the suppliers regarding the search for raw
 materials in the long run. 

Risk of lack and increasing of raw materials to produce solar cells
         The important raw material of Solar Cell is wafer which is produced from 
Solar-grade silicon. Currently the tendency of wafer price is increase. Nevertheless,
 At the PHOTON International 1st Solar Silicon Conference it is expected that after 
2007 or 2008, the lack of solar-grade silicon problem would be minor since many
 companies are joining together to construct a solar-grade silicon factory including 
Ekarat Solar Co.,Ltd. received good cooperation from the suppliers regarding the 
search for raw materials in the long run. So Ekarat Solar Co.,Ltd. expected not to
 face lack of wafer. However, the price of solar-grade silicon may increa
se and affect production even if the average price was US$ 36 per kilogram in 2004 
will be increased to US$54 per kilogram or more than 50 per cent which will affect 
the production of the Solar System 3-8 per cent only because solar cell uses 13 grams
 of solar-grade silicon per watt only.(Source: Photon International, June 2004) 

Risk of government policy on alternative energy 
         The government has increased fix 8 per cent of the commercial energy to be 
from solar cell within 2011 by The National Energy Strategy to produce energy
 from the Renewable Portfolio Standard "RPS". RPS is a standard set to produce
 new electricity energy from fossil which can act as an alternative energy of RPS 5
 per cent. However, the policy is still unclear and the existing problems may 
significantly affect the financial status of Ekarat Solar Co.,Ltd. Nevertheless from
 increasing of price of oil so the government tries to find alternative energy
 including Ekarat Solar Co.,Ltd. can sell solar cell for overseas customers or 
local manufacturing that required alternative energy so the unclear about
 alternative government policy not affect financial status of Ekarat Solar 
Co.,Ltd.

Risk of company's liquidity from current liabilities
         On March 31, 2006 total liabilities of AKR (excluding its subsidiary company)
 was Baht 507.02 million. This includes the agreement of credit line that fix the 
company and its subsidiary affiliates to be maintained debt to equity ratio no
 more than 3:1 times that may affect the company's liquidity. However AKR
 (excluding its subsidiary company) have Debt to Equity Ratio 0.81 times 
(as of March 31, 2006) and it is expected to reduce to 0.46 times after Initial
 Public Offering. Moreover, after exit the rehabilitation plan, the company's
 performance has been improved accordingly and the company is in the 
process of negotiating to expand term of payment from its creditors. And 
the company also as request the financial institutions to expand its credit term
 loan. Therefore, the company and its subsidiary company will not face a 
liquidity problem.

Risk of paying dividends 
         The credit loans from banks indicate the company must inform the bank 
in writing 15 days in advance regarding the dividends payment to shareholders
 since 2004 and that the company does not delay the payment to be made to the
 bank and there are no liabilities, interest or fee that if including the company 
retained deficit. However after the company passed the rehabilitation plan, 
include the tendency of the economic situation that may improve respectively.
 The company and affiliates gaining retained earnings of 2006 onwards.

Risk that the shareholders are unable to perform their role as shareholders
         On May 30, 2006, the criminal court made a judgment for Mr. Panya 
Tantiyavarong, The Chairman of the Audit Committee, who formerly held a 
position of The Chairman of the State Audit Commission, is charged for the
 misconduct behavior causing damage to some personnel. The public prosecutor
 and Mr. Prathan Dabpetch are prosecutors against Mr. Panya Tantiyavarong,
 formerly The Chairman of the Kingdom's Monetary Inspection, have proposed
 a panel of candidates to be selected as governor of the Kingdom's Monetary 
Inspection but the process was not done according to the procedures of the 
committee. This member of the committee is under an appeal at the appeal court
 as the case is still not resolved and there is no policy to change the member 
of the committee. This is result of risk for the company because the member
 of the committee cannot perform his duty as the member of the committee of
 the shareholders to audit the company. Once the case and court judged that the
 member of the committee had misconduct and he could not perform his duty 
as a certified public accountant, the company would assign a new person to 
replace Mr. Panya Tantiyavarong.

Legal disputes                                  - None -
